An analysis of data on educational attainment and deprivation in Scotland

Author: T. Hellen

14/04/2022

Summary

In this report, we investigate data on demographics in Scotland, particularly relating to educational attainment and focusing especially on school attendance, alcohol consumption, employment rate and access to broadband. We also take a look at the relationships between educational attainment, income rate, mental health, drive time to primary and secondary schools and crime rate.

This report uses investigative methods such as histograms, boxplots, normal Q-Q plots, hypothesis tests, scatter graphs and regression models.

The results indicate an overall higher attainment from Edinburgh over Glasgow and that a higher attendance, higher income rate and better mental health has a positive affect on student attainment.

Introduction

The data used in this report are taken from the 2020 Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation (SIMD), a tool used by government bodies to support policy-making and funding. It is used to help understand the circumstances and outcomes of people living in the most deprived areas in Scotland.

The aim of this report is to understand how certain variables, such as where people live, how people live, the circumstances they live in and the resources available to them affect educational attainment.

The data include various variables for different “data zones” in Scotland. Data zones are small geographical areas typically containing a population of between 500 and 1000 people. There are 6,976 data zones in total in Scotland, but the analysis in this report focuses on a sample of 400 of them, of which 100 are from the Glasgow City, 100 are from City of Edinburgh, and 200 are from elsewhere in Scotland.

The data set contains many different variables, of which we will focus in particular on:

  • Attainment - the attainment of school leavers
  • Attendance - the percentage of school pupil attendance
  • Alcohol - hospital stays related to alcohol use
  • Employment Rate - the percentage of people who are employment deprived
  • Broadband - the percentage of premises without access to superfast broadband, in this case at least 30Mb/s download speed
  • Income Rate - the percentage of people who are income deprived
  • Mental Health - the proportion of population being prescribed drugs for anxiety, depression or psychosis
  • Drive Time - the average drive time to a primary school and secondary school in minutes
  • Crime Rate - the recorded crimes of violence, sexual offences, domestic housebreaking, vandalism, drugs offences and common assault per 10,000 people

This study helps the government understand where they need to direct their funding. It shows which variables affect educational attainment, to help parents, students and teachers in improving and optimising grades achieved when students leave school. It shows the cause and effect of different attainment in different areas.

Methods

We use various methods of exploratory data analysis, including presenting box plots between Edinburgh and Glasgow to compare their educational attainment, plotting histograms and normal Q-Q plots of Glasgow and Edinburgh to compare their distributions, and performing hypothesis tests to also compare the variance of both distributions of data.

We use a matrix of scatter plots and calculate Pearson sample correlation coefficients to gain a numerical understanding of the relationship between attainment and the other variables described above. We focus on comparing attainment with school attendance, using a least squares linear regression to plot an appropriate regression line on a scatter graph. We use a hypothesis test to check whether the regression is useful for making predictions.

We compare attainment to the further variables mentioned above by using another matrix of scatter graphs, and calculating Pearson sample correlation coefficients to make note of any noticeable and sizeable correlations, then compare them in histograms, using frequency density for ease of comparability.

Results

Comparing educational attainment between the cities of Glasgow and Edinburgh

In this section, we focus on the available data for Glasgow and Edinburgh, for each of which the data set contains 100 observations (data zones). For these data zones, the following box plots summarise the distribution of the educational attainment variable:

Figure 1: The distribution of educational attainment in Glasgow and Edinburgh

These box plots show the differences between Edinburgh and Glasgow’s educational attainment. The mean of Edinburgh’s attainment grades are higher than Glasgow, however, on average more of Glasgow’s students get higher grades than Edinburgh’s, from looking at the upper quartiles. Glasgow has a larger spread of grades than Edinburgh, with a lower minimum and a higher maximum.

As further numerical summaries of overall attainment and variability in attainment, we compute the sample means and variances respectively. The sample mean attainments for Glasgow and Edinburgh are \(\bar{x}_G=\) 5.3666 and \(\bar{x}_E =\) 5.3941, and the sample variances are \(s^2_G =\) 0.2038 and \(s^2_E =\) 0.3772.

To investigate the distributions in more detail, the following shows histograms of the educational attainment in Glasgow and Edinburgh, along with normal Q-Q plots for the data.

Figure 2: Histograms and accompanying normal QQ plots of educational attainment for Glasgow and Edinburgh

The histograms show with more clarity Glasgow’s normal distribution.Fewer of Glasgow’s students attain high grades than Edinburgh, and more of them achieve middling grades between 5.0 and 5.5.

From the Q-Q plots we can see a couple outliers on both ends for each city, where some students will have gotten abnormally high or low grades. We also see that Edinburgh’s distribution doesn’t quite fit the suggested model. Edinburgh has curvature in opposite directions at both ends, suggesting that the sample distribution has lighter tails than the theoretical distribution.

To investigate whether or not the variance of attainment is the same in Glasgow and Edinburgh, we consider the null and alternative hypotheses \(H_0: \sigma^2_G = \sigma^2_E\) vs \(H_0: \sigma^2_G \neq \sigma^2_E\) and can use a test based on the F distribution with \(v_1=v_2=100\). If \(H_0\) is true, and assuming the data are normally distributed, random and from independent populations, then \(\frac{(n_G-1)s^2_G}{\sigma^2_G}=\) 0.1428 \(\sim X_{nG-1}^2\) and \(\frac{(n_E-1)s^2_E}{\sigma^2_E}=\) 0.48399 \(\sim X_{nE-1}^2\) have a chi-squared distribution.

The value of the F statistic that we compute from the data is 0.5403596. The 5% and 95% quantiles of the null distribution are 0.3635765, 0.8031007, and since 1, the true ratio of the variances, lies outside this region we therefore have strong evidence against the null hypothesis and reject \(H_0\), concluding that the population variability is not the same for Edinburgh and Glasgow at the 5% significance level.

Investigating the relationship between educational attainment and other variables

In this section we consider all of the data zones.

The following plot shows the relationship between the various variables described in the Introduction section above.

Figure 3: Matrix scatterplot for the relationship between educational attainment, attendance, alcohol, employment rate and broadband

The corresponding numerical values for the Pearson sample correlation coefficients between these variables are

Attainment Attendance Alcohol Employment Rate Broadband
Attainment 1.0000 0.6912 -0.4937 -0.6177 0.1593
Attendance 0.6912 1.0000 -0.5401 -0.7283 0.2459
Alcohol -0.4937 -0.5401 1.0000 0.7550 -0.1875
Employment Rate -0.6177 -0.7283 0.7550 1.0000 -0.2125
Broadband 0.1593 0.2459 -0.1875 -0.2125 1.0000

We can conclude that attainment and attendance have a strong positive correlation - the higher a student’s attendance, the higher the grades attained when they leave school. We see that number of hospital stays and percentage of unemployed people are positively correlated, and that these both negatively affect attendance and educational attainment. Broadband speed has a negligible affect on any of the other variables, although it does have a small positive correlation with attainment.

We plot again as follows the attainment rate versus the attendance, with an added line of best fit for a regression model.

Figure 4: Educational attainment rate against attendance, with a line of best fit for a regression model

The line of best fit is of the form attainment = \(\beta_0\) + \(\beta_1 \times\) attendance where the least-squares estimates of \(\beta_0=\) 2.2232 and \(\beta_1=\) 4.0788. The value of the statistic \(t = { \hat{\beta}_1}/\left( \hat{\sigma} / \sqrt{ (n-1)s_x^2 }\right)\), which is useful for testing \(H_0: \beta_1 = 0\) vs \(H_1: \beta_1 \neq 0\) and has a normal distribution under \(H_0\), equals 19.0834. This corresponds to a \(p\)-value of 0 confirming that there is sufficient evidence against \(H_0\), and therefore suggests that the regression is useful in making predictions.

A brief investigation into the relationship between educational attainment and further variables

In this section we consider the relationship between educational attainment, income rate, mental health, drive primary and drive secondary, and crime rate.

The following plot shows the relationship between the various variables described above.

Figure 5: Matrix scatterplot for the relationship between educational attainment, income rate, mental health, drive time - primary, drive time - secondary and crime rate

Attainment Income Rate Mental Health Drive Time - Primary Drive Time - Secondary Crime Rate
Attainment 1.00 -0.64 -0.49 0.28 0.18 NA
Income Rate -0.64 1.00 0.78 -0.31 -0.21 NA
Mental Health -0.49 0.78 1.00 -0.25 -0.16 NA
Drive Time - Primary 0.28 -0.31 -0.25 1.00 0.49 NA
Drive Time - Secondary 0.18 -0.21 -0.16 0.49 1.00 NA
Crime Rate NA NA NA NA NA NA

Crime rate has no affect on any of the other variables, whereas attainment, income rate and mental health have the strongest correlations. As the percentage of those on low income increases, the attainment decreases and those on drugs prescribed due to mental health also increases.

There is a weak correlation between both drive times and attainment, which could be due to outliers.

The following plots take a closer look at attainment, income rate and mental health through histograms.

Figure 6: Histograms of educational attainment, income rate and mental health for Glasgow, Edinburgh and other regions

The percentage of income deprived is lowest in Edinburgh - due to this they have the largest frequency density of high grades, and lowest amount of drugs prescribed due to mental health problems. The educational attainment in other regions is a normal distribution like Glasgow, but skews further to the right, indicating a higher mean for those areas.

Glasgow has the widest spread of income rate, and a bimodal distribution for income rate and mental health. Glasgow’s percentage of people with prescribed drugs for mental health is skewed the furthest to the right, with both the income rate and mental health indicating a direct affect on educational attainment, like in the other regions, where income and mental health positively affect the educational attainment.

Conclusions

We have investigated various characteristics of data available for geographical areas in Scotland called “data zones”, focusing in particular on Glasgow and Edinburgh. Overall, Edinburgh’s students attain higher grades than Glasgow, which has a slightly lower mean.

Attendance has the biggest effect on attainment from looking at the scatterplots - the more a student attends class, the higher grades they get when they leave school.

We also found that high income rate and better mental health have a direct positive impact on educational attainment.

There are some limitations of the current study. The data is only from one year, looking at data from a spread of several years could allow us to compare which variables affect attainment. The data we are looking at doesn’t specify the ages, this would be useful in looking at parents effects on student’s attainment, and what could be due to other circumstances.

A future study could investigate how government funding and charities can help with disadvantages that affect a student’s education. It could investigate student’s downtime and attitude towards education. It could conduct further hypothesis tests to confirm if the noted relationships are significant.

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)
scottish.data <- read.csv("scottishData.csv", header=TRUE)

glasgow=subset(scottish.data, Council_area=="Glasgow City")
edinburgh=subset(scottish.data, Council_area=="City of Edinburgh")
#glasgow and edinburgh against attainment
boxplot(edinburgh[,c(18)],glasgow[,c(18)],
range=0,col=(c('#0000FF88','#0000CC88')), names=c('Glasgow','Ediburgh'), xlab='Educational Attainment', ylab='Cities', main='Boxplots for Glasgow and Edinburgh', horizontal=TRUE)

m.glas=mean(glasgow[,c(18)])
m.edin=mean(edinburgh[,c(18)])
v.glas=var(glasgow[,c(18)])
v.edin=var(edinburgh[,c(18)])
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
hist(glasgow[,c(18)], xlab='Educational Attainment', ylab='No. Data Zones', main='Histogram: Glasgow', col='#0000FF88')
hist(edinburgh[,c(18)], xlab='Educational Attainment', ylab='No. Data Zones', main='Histogram: Edinburgh', col='#0000CC88', ylim=c(0,40))
mtext('Histograms and QQ plots for Educational Attainment', side=3, line=-1.5, outer=TRUE, font=2, cex=1.6)
qqnorm(glasgow[,c(18)], col='#0000FF88', pch=19, main='Normal Q-Q Plot: Glasgow', ylim=c(4.0,6.5))
qqnorm(edinburgh[,c(18)], col='#0000CC88', pch=19, main='Normal Q-Q Plot: Edinburgh')

test=var.test(glasgow$Attainment, edinburgh$Attainment, alternative = 'two.sided')
chi_G=(99*v.glas**2)/(m.glas**2)
chi_E=(99*v.edin**2)/(m.edin**2)

upper.panel<-function(x, y){
  points(x,y, pch=20, col=c('#00009950'))
  r <- round(cor(x, y, method=c("pearson")), digits=2)
  txt <- paste0("R = ", r)
  usr <- par("usr"); on.exit(par(usr))
  par(usr = c(0, 1, 0, 1))
  text(0.5, 0.9, txt)
}
pairs(scottish.data[,c(18,17,11,8,31)],upper.panel = upper.panel, lower.panel = upper.panel, labels=c('Attainment','Attendance','Alcohol','Employment Rate','Broadband'), main='Matrix of scatter graphs for the relationship \nbetween educational attainment and other variables')
